segments.text: We started out to get to Tunisia as quick as possible.
And the only way we had to go was to walk across the top of Africa.
But the regimental commander said, it was raining and we were going to have our feet wet and we were going to be crippled.
So he said, just don't go any further.
I'll be back later.
And he went into Iran.
to some motor pool and gave a hand receipt for a whole flock of vehicles, and off we went.
And we drove all the way across North Africa.
And in those mountains, it was cold.
And as I said, I woke up one day, my ring was gone.
And I didn't have any idea.
I figured I'd flung it off my hand during the night in that cold.
But about two to three weeks later,
A driver was cleaning the Jeep, and he found it down in the floorboard of the Jeep under a lot of stuff.
And so I was, of course, real glad to get it back.
Are there any stories that you have where somebody spotted you wearing an Aggie ring?
Well, I've had a lot of people through the years say, what's that ring?
And I say, it's an Aggie ring.
Yeah, it's an Aggie ring.
And hear me here, they want to know what the ring is for.
See, they bathe us three times a week and shave me every now and then, too, with an electric razor.
After I got
I had this last operation, Haskell.
I went from being independent to totally dependent.
I'll tell you about that in a few minutes, but anyway.
And when they go to baby, sometimes that ring comes off.
But they all know what that ring is now.
Here, as soon as I get through the breakfast,
They'll take you down and bathe you.
And they bathe me three times a week.
I cannot do anything, unfortunately.
I had a rebuilt knee in here.
And I wore it out pushing this one.
And it was the, I believe, the second or third one I had.
Anyway, the doctor told us there were two doctors that they recommended in the College of Medicine.
I mean, Texas Medical Center down here, that would have taken them out and rebuilt them.
And so Dr. Tullis took this one out, and it was the worst, he said, the worst condition he had ever seen a knee.
It naturally would be.
It was full of infection and bone fragments, and they took it all out of there and rebuilt it.
And for a long time, we had a piece of bone that wasn't knitting.
I finally ended up getting a big skin graft on this knee.
And as a result, I've not been able to walk a whole lot since.
When they took the thing out, he said he'd put a new one in.
And in time, he thought I'd be able to walk on it.
I don't think I'll ever walk again because every step hurts.
They told me to get these shoes.
I call them New Comfort or something, anyway.
They don't slip or slide.
Used to, when I'd get up, I'd slip or slide, and this would hurt more.
But now, and I took a week in the hospital in Houston where they worked on me and tried to teach me a little bit better how to walk and those things.
But I have a hard time because that knee has not healed yet.
I can do a lot of things, but it'll get better sooner or later.
I hope.
Let's see.
Describe for you the great events of commissioning and commencement day.
Sure.
I can't think that far back.
That would have been the spring of 38.
Commissioning, let me think.
Well, we graduated in the morning and were commissioned in the afternoon, if I remember this right.
Also, at that time, I believe we had a review for the reviewing officers.
Came from Fort Sam.
Oh, and do you remember Major R?
Who?
Did you ever hear of Major R?
Well, he would have been a captain for a thousand years for this reason.
No one knows why, but when the visiting officer came in on the train from San Antonio, they sent Major Orr down to beat him.
So he walked up to him and didn't salute him, nothing.
He just stuck his hand out and says, Orr is my name, O-R-R. God, I'm telling you, that man, that colonel, I should have gone through the truth.
And he...
And he had a dog named Rip.
Rip Orr?
Rip Orr.
And we would go to Camp Bullets in the summer.
Let me close this door.
Rip went everywhere.
Rip went everywhere that Major Orr went.
Captain Orr, he finally got promoted to Major, though.
I believe he was the Major when he went to meet the Colonel.
Anyway, we'd be out on the fire line at camp, putting bullets, and old Rip would be out there, too.
And I remember Orr said, Rip!

gets your ass off the funny line before you get perforated and always with his nasal tone you know but uh we had a commissioning was i said we just it was a formal ceremony and that's in the afternoon after graduation in the morning and after we were commissioned i believe that we commissioned we put on a
Of course, that was a highlight in all our lives, that we were in the thing.
See, everybody didn't get an advance contract.
If you got an advance contract, you got a commission.
And that's when you got rid of the government-issued uniform and bought your own.
And I remember that, again, I got one of everything I needed in a uniform for $100.
And Lord, I don't know what that cost them.
But I do know that it was much, much later when the war came on that I had to buy another uniform.
A commencement was held at Guyon Hall.
Let me think.
I don't know where it was held.
I guess it was held everywhere.
Do you remember who the speaker was?
Who came, friends and family, who came for your commissioning and commencement?
I didn't have anybody.
Let me think of it.
Graduation and commencement.
See, my grandmother raised me.
Yes.
By this time, she had retired and moved.
She had moved to Tyler to be with her daughter.
And I don't think we had anybody come.
Did Freda come?
I don't remember.
I'm sure she didn't because we didn't start going together until my junior year, I believe.
I can't remember all those things, really.
As you graduated, what kind of life did you think you were going to be pursuing?
Well, I thought I would be working in landscape work, but there weren't any jobs available.
The guys in front of us had gone to work for Lamberts in Dallas, and they were shelving manure.
So I thought it was my scoop.
And I went back to school and got my master's.
I had 20 hours of work over my master's.
And so I got to do my master's in one year.
At A&M?
At A&M, which would be a term paper now anywhere else.
And I do the thesis on the use of native plants in landscape design.
Who was your chairman?
Who directed it?
Mr. Hensel.
But they gave me the chairman of the English department on the committee.
And he read a line.
I couldn't buy and pay to have it typed.
But he read a line so bad, 14 pages, that I had to have redone and no one to do it with.
And he complained, he said, this boy has personified all these plants.
They're just like people to him.
I said, yes, that's right.
He used it that way.
Was that Dr. Cofer?
No, Summey.
Oh, Dr. Summey.
Yeah.
Dr. Summey.
That threw me for a loop.
And I spent a week in the hospital after I got through with all of that.
See, I did that thing in nine months, which was too quick.
Anyway, I spent a week in the hospital.
And month of that, meanwhile, I got a good job with that master's degree.
Jacques Goebbels, who I mentioned earlier, brought this young man up.
I mean, he was brought over by
Mr. Gilchrist, to start the roadside beautification program.
And Jack Goebbels did it.
So I got a job in District 9 as roadside beautification chairman.
And that was $140 a month.
That was big money.
What part of state was District 9?
Waco.
Waco with Edwards.
And there were seven counties around as far as Hamilton County.
And I worked the first eight or nine months in the soil laboratory.
And Mr. Puckett was the district engineer.
He came out one day and said, well, I put you out here to find out if you could work.
And he says, you don't mind working, so we're going to give you
We're going to make you a roadside beautician for this district.
So get your car and get ready to do the roadside work.
Well, then we had a person like that in every district in the county, I mean in the state.
And we had regular meetings and lectures and seminars and things.
And we'd have to write books and little pamphlets on this.
So we saw the beginning of the Texas Highway.
that spread all over the country.
But John Goebbels was a good man.
As you were getting ready to start that first job, how well prepared did it seem A&M had made you for that kind of work?
Well, I thought good.
I was well pleased with what I did, and
I'm very happy all the way through school under Ms. Henson's leadership, because if it was something we didn't need to know, he'd tell us.
And he didn't say a word, but he'd tell us.
And we got good advice.
And also the man that I told you about in entomology, Dr. Little, I believe is his name, both of them were good teachers, excellent teachers.
And Mitch was a great mentor.
He'd tell me all kinds of things.
I have to say, every time I went back to A&M, I went to see him.
And we spent many happy hours together working on these things.
But I thought I was as well prepared as anybody as I could be in a new field.
It was a brand new field.
They didn't even know what I was taking at home.
Somebody asked my grandmother, what's Robert taking?
Well, I don't know what he's having to leave me alone, which I thought was pretty good advice.
Now, when did you buy your first car?
I got my message in.
So it's after you.
After you leave school?
Oh, yeah, after I leave school.
I didn't need a car until I got to do the roadside work.
Now, did you ever hitchhike when you were an Aggie?
Oh, yeah.
Describe how an Aggie hitchhiked.
Going my way.
Of course, you know we had regular stations.
You stayed in line, took your turn in line.
Of course, my problem was, when I was in Transactor Franklin, coming back to see Russ, there wasn't anybody coming this way.
Or they were already full.
And I know one time, during my senior year,
My grandmother had sold the hotel and moved to Tyler, and we, a whole bunch of us, got stuck in Palestine.
I think there's 25 or 30 of us in there.
And there wasn't much, I mean, tell you, we thought we were going to spend the week in Palestine.
And all of a sudden, everybody got waked up that
The bus, a local bus, I need to know the kid's name, picked everybody up and took them all the way to college.
My gosh.
That was something.
Now, if you were going north to Franklin, where did you catch the ride in College Station?
Called it Brian.
Where?
On the corner of the courthouse, across the street from the courthouse.
Now, how did you get from the campus up to Brian?
Same way, some way.
Oh.
Yeah.
With your thumb?
With my thumb.
And a long time as you were going to Franklin, you didn't get a very good priority in Hearn.
People were going to go further than that.
They didn't want you taking the ride just to Franklin, 13 miles.
Did you ever have any bad experience hitchhiking?
No.
Did you have any interesting experiences that you'd like to share?
Rode with some interesting people?
Well, nothing special except that bus incident.
We got 30-some people on one corner and couldn't get out.
We're still in there, I believe it.
While you were an undergraduate, what did you do in the summers?
Worked.
Where?
Right there.
You stayed on the campus?
I never went home.
And worked full time?
I never went home.
Where did you and your buddies go to have some fun other than hardlickers?
No, you never went to hardlickers.
Where did you go for fun on a Saturday night?
I didn't have to have any fun.
I probably washed pots all day How often did you go home to Franklin?

I didn't go home I didn't go I was going to work I needed to work to get a little money to go to school next year and I was to go and then you were Did you by chance encounter Mr. Gilchrist soon after he got here?
Oh, yes.
Describe him, please.
Well, he was, I thought, a very good president.
Everybody was a little bit aghast to hire somebody from the University of Texas, you know, to take that job.
No, he had a good vision, and he was determined that we would get the roadside program underway, and that's when I brought Jock Goebbels over and...
I enjoyed Mr. Gilchrist very much.
Henry, his son, told me that when they first moved here that he was homesick for Austin because the campus was so rural and isolated, he thought.
But his dad bought him a bike as a bribe to make him happy.
I hadn't heard that one.
After he retired...
He had his garage made into a den in our study.
And he had all kinds of citations on all the walls.
And she collected unusual bottles.
And I had a green bottle shaped like a human.
And I gave it to her.
But no, I enjoyed Mr. Gilchrist very much.
He had some friends in Mumford.
I don't know their name.
Anyway, she was a great roadside person.
I can't think of her name.
Too many years.
Well, that's beside the point now.
On the campus where all the faculty lived,
was, describe that as a, that was a little community in its own.
A little community in its own.
And I was told that to get people there, they had to have housing, because there wasn't any place for them to live in that area.
And I remember where they, the different ones, Dean's house, and as you went from now, what would it be, the MSC corner, Mr. Hensel's house was on that corner.
And over where the football dormitory is, there were two streets over there that had faculty houses on them, too.
And that's where Mr. McGinnis lived.
He was a professor in the department.
keep Frida farm when she came down.
She can stay with them.
Did any of those faculty folks ask you to help them with their flower gardens or anything like that?
No.
Did you go on court trips?
Oh, yeah.
Describe what a court trip was like.
How did you get there and what did you all do?
Well, they were always
training back in the early days.
And you were supposed to go, but you were irrespective.
They didn't care.
You would end up in Fort Worth, which is at the Union Station, and get organized and do the parade.
And they also would...
My freshman year, not having enough money, they said, we'll get you on the train, don't worry.
They got me on the train with the seats like this, put me back in the man's suitcase in front of me, and I rode forward that way.
And more than one kid did that way.
You'd be expected to be at the Union Station in Fort Worth at 8 o'clock on a Saturday morning, and you'd parade down.
And that was it.
And you went to Austin or Houston each year also?
I mean, we went to Austin, I know.
Dallas or Fort Worth?
That was for alternate years.
And then Austin and Houston alternate years.
Did you ever have any bad core trip experiences?
No.
I don't remember going to Houston.
Maybe we did.
But I didn't have any bad experiences.
The student indulgences of the time, people smoked?
Did the Aggies smoke much?
They weren't allowed to smoke.
And they went to Mr. Ed's, was whiskey.
Uncle Ed's.
Where did they buy whiskey?
Don't touch it to this day, so I don't know.
I know that there was talk of going across the county line somewhere.
Going towards Snook to Whiskey Bridge.
Okay.
Okay.
And did you and your buddies know the words marijuana?
No.
And cocaine?
Never heard of any of that.
Did some people chew tobacco in that era?
Oh, they made the certain...
The band, I believe, made the kids chew tobacco at the first baseball game and got them all sick.
Certain organizations made the kids chew tobacco at the first baseball game and that made them all sick.
Did you go to, as an undergraduate, did you go to an Aggie muster?
I never heard of muster.
Before the war, you had not heard of them?
That's what I... Do you have that from any people?
No, you're saying the same thing.
I have the impression that muster really became a big Aggie tradition as a result of the... Corregidor.
Corregidor muster.
To be perfectly frank, I don't believe I ever heard of Muster, the four years I was there.
And that may have been again because I was working on it.
There's a lot of things I didn't participate in because I was working all that.
I got a call from the Alfred Walt people one day.
I heard of Alfred Walt.
I don't know what it was because I didn't participate.
I was working.
I had to work to stay in school.
And it's just that way.
All right, now this one I think I know, though.
Did you attend to silver taps?
Yes, we had silver taps back then.
Describe it, what it meant.
Where was it held?
Clean place still now, I believe.
Did you and your buddies take Silver Tap seriously?
Oh, yes.
Very serious.
We thought that was the most serious thing on the campus at the time.
And I know that they played from up on the dome up there.
And it was very impressive still in the night.
What is it that creates Aggie spirit, Aggie pride?
Aggie pride.
It's just the fact that when you get into it, it never gets out of your system.
As you rub shoulders day to day and you have the feeling of belonging to an organization and you get bonded together,
Aggie pride is just the fact that when you came there, you were nothing.
You got to be somebody.
And for the first time, you knew people very closely, became very close friends.
And like I said, I think the most severe blow I had was when David Murphy was killed in an airplane right at the beginning of our senior year.
He had already asked me to be a Ross volunteer, which I turned down.
He was on the Coastal Artillery of all places, too.
I think we got to know each other in class.
I went back to the cemetery every time, but I finally quit going.
What are the other events other than Silver Taps that helped to create
that pride, that spirit?
Well, at that time, it was the fact that you belonged to a group, a special group.
I belonged to A Infantry, and I've always enjoyed those people.
They've been very close.
In fact, one of my very best friends in A Infantry just died this summer.
It's the cohesiveness and the fact that you belong and you know you belong.
And everybody's good to each other.
As you were preparing to leave A&M for that first job, did you feel well prepared for that task?
I thought I was well prepared for anything but A&M because of the new program.
They're starting brand new in Texas.
And of course,
The Texas Wildfire, the Texas Roadside Development Program has spread all over the country.
I know where it started and who did it.
We used to take a
He used to mow the field and get the straw and throw them on the road.
Now they have wildflower farms you can buy them by the pounds.
And you know what they do now?
They put them in capsules, gelatin capsules, and just throw them on the roadside and they melt and go right there.
Were you concerned about what was happening in Europe at the time you left A&M?
Yes.
In fact, when I was working at the highway department, Mr. Puckett, an old agate, would come out every morning at 10 o'clock and turn his radio on, and we'd listen to what was happening over there.
We were all very much aware of it.
And we pretty well followed the development of it all the way up.
I'm almost finished now with this first part.
What have we left out of your student experiences that we should have covered?
Student experiences?
Let me see here.
I might lose, but I...
This is, of course, the thing that I did.
I made fun of those sophomores, which people thought I was crazy to do, because they knew I was going to get patted on.
And I didn't care, because I didn't think they could hurt me, and they didn't.
Ga Ga Kama was the only man who hurt me.
And I never did come back.
When he hit me that one lick on the third floor, the heart, oh, I just kept going.
But the rest of them, I didn't care.
They didn't bother me much.
Didn't let it bother me, because I figured
